Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX Parser
Note: ================================================================
Note: Parses LaTeX source code into Abstract Syntax Tree (AST).
Note: Comprehensive coverage of LaTeX document structure and commands.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_lexer.runa" as LaTeXLexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ================================================================
Note: AST Node Type Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant NODE_DOCUMENT as Integer is 1
Constant NODE_PREAMBLE as Integer is 2
Constant NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS as Integer is 3
Constant NODE_PACKAGE as Integer is 4
Constant NODE_ENVIRONMENT as Integer is 5
Constant NODE_SECTION as Integer is 6
Constant NODE_COMMAND as Integer is 7
Constant NODE_TEXT_BLOCK as Integer is 8
Constant NODE_MATH_INLINE as Integer is 9
Constant NODE_MATH_DISPLAY as Integer is 10
Constant NODE_LIST as Integer is 11
Constant NODE_LIST_ITEM as Integer is 12
Constant NODE_FIGURE as Integer is 13
Constant NODE_TABLE as Integer is 14
Constant NODE_CITATION as Integer is 15
Constant NODE_REFERENCE as Integer is 16
Constant NODE_LABEL as Integer is 17
Constant NODE_TEXT_FORMATTING as Integer is 18
Constant NODE_GROUP as Integer is 19
Constant NODE_ARGUMENT as Integer is 20

Note: ================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser is a minimal three-field state: token-list pointer (borrowed from lexer), cursor index, and per-parse error list. LaTeX parsing is mostly linear (preamble then body) so we don't need a full lookahead buffer — peek/peek_type provide one token of lookahead which is sufficient for LaTeX's LL(1)-with-recovery shape.
@End Reasoning
Type called "LaTeXParser":
    tokens as Integer  Note: Pointer to list of tokens
    current as Integer  Note: Current token index
    errors as Integer  Note: Pointer to list of parse errors
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Parser Initialization
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 24-byte struct (3 slots) and creates the error list eagerly. tokens_list is borrowed (owned by the lexer); current starts at 0 so the first peek returns the first token.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_parser" that takes tokens_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 0, tokens_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 8, 0  Note: current index

    Let errors_list be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 16, errors_list

    Return parser_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Token Navigation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the raw token pointer at the cursor or 0 if past end; ListCore.get_from_list handles the bounds check, so we don't duplicate it here. Productions use peek to look without committing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let tokens_list be proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 0
    Let current_index be proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 8

    Return proc get_from_list from ListCore with tokens_list, current_index
End Process

@Reasoning:
peek_type extracts only the type tag (offset 0) from the current token so productions can Match on it without dereferencing the full token struct. Returning TOKEN_EOF when peek yields 0 unifies "past end" with "saw EOF token" so callers handle both with one branch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_type" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token_ptr be proc peek from parser_ptr

    If token_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Return proc read_integer from Memory with token_ptr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
advance returns the consumed token so productions can pattern-match on it without a separate peek-then-advance pair. Cursor bump happens after the peek so the returned pointer is the just-consumed token, not the next one.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token_ptr be proc peek from parser_ptr

    Let current_index be proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 8
    proc write_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 8, current_index plus 1

    Return token_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
expect is the canonical recursive-descent primitive ("eat this terminal or error"). On mismatch we record a recoverable error and return 0 so callers can choose to error-recover (skip to a known sync point) or propagate the failure.
@End Reasoning
Process called "expect" that takes parser_ptr as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

    If token_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return proc advance from parser_ptr
    Otherwise:
        proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unexpected token"
        Return 0
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
match is the soft counterpart to expect: it consumes the token if it matches OR leaves the cursor alone otherwise, returning 1/0. Productions use match for optional terminals (e.g., optional [...]) where absence is not an error.
@End Reasoning
Process called "match" that takes parser_ptr as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let current_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

    If current_type is equal to token_type:
        proc advance from parser_ptr
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Main Parsing Entry Point
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
A LaTeX document is structurally just "preamble + \begin{document}...\end{document}"; we model that directly as a NODE_DOCUMENT with two children. Document outside the begin/end is treated as preamble even though strictly only \documentclass and packages should appear there — this leniency matches what TeX itself accepts.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let document_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with document_ptr, 0, NODE_DOCUMENT

    Note: Parse preamble (everything before \begin{document})
    Let preamble_ptr be proc parse_preamble from parser_ptr
    proc write_integer from Memory with document_ptr, 8, preamble_ptr

    Note: Parse document environment
    Let body_ptr be proc parse_document_body from parser_ptr
    proc write_integer from Memory with document_ptr, 16, body_ptr

    Return document_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Preamble Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Preamble parsing runs until \begin{document} or EOF; each iteration dispatches on the current token type. \documentclass is special-cased because spec says it must come first; \usepackage gets its own production for argument parsing; other \commands fall through to the general parse_command. Unknown tokens advance silently so a malformed preamble doesn't spin forever.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_preamble" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let preamble_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with preamble_ptr, 0, NODE_PREAMBLE

    Let items_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Note: Parse document class
    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_DOCUMENTCLASS:
        Let doc_class be proc parse_document_class from parser_ptr
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with items_list, doc_class
    End If

    Note: Parse packages and other preamble items until \begin{document}
    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_BEGIN:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_USEPACKAGE:

                    Let package be proc parse_package from parser_ptr
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with items_list, package
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_COMMAND:

                        Let command be proc parse_command from parser_ptr
                        proc add_to_list from ListCore with items_list, command
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Skip unexpected token
                        proc advance from parser_ptr
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc write_integer from Memory with preamble_ptr, 8, items_list

    Return preamble_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
\documentclass has the shape "\documentclass[opts]{class}"; the optional [...] is parsed conditionally on peek_type, then the required {class} argument is consumed. Storing options and class_name as separate child pointers (offsets 8 and 16) lets backends emit either the LaTeX form or a different markup format without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_document_class" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let doc_class_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with doc_class_ptr, 0, NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_DOCUMENTCLASS

    Note: Parse optional options
    Let options_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set options_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with doc_class_ptr, 8, options_ptr

    Note: Parse required class name
    Let class_name_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with doc_class_ptr, 16, class_name_ptr

    Return doc_class_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
\usepackage syntax mirrors \documentclass; same parsing structure with options-then-name. We use NODE_PACKAGE instead of NODE_DOCUMENT_CLASS so downstream stages can treat packages distinctly (e.g., a HIR backend mapping LaTeX packages to library imports needs to recognize this specifically).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_package" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let package_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with package_ptr, 0, NODE_PACKAGE

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_USEPACKAGE

    Note: Parse optional options
    Let options_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set options_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with package_ptr, 8, options_ptr

    Note: Parse required package name
    Let package_name_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with package_ptr, 16, package_name_ptr

    Return package_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Document Body Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The document body is parsed by reusing parse_content_until_end with "document" as the sentinel — this means the document environment is parsed identically to any nested environment, which simplifies the parser. We expect \begin and then consume the required {document} argument before delegating to the generic content loop.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_document_body" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect \begin{document}
    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_BEGIN

    Let begin_arg be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    Note: Parse content until \end{document}
    Let content_list be proc parse_content_until_end with parser_ptr, "document"

    Return content_list
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Content Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The generic content loop terminates on \end OR EOF (the latter being recoverable in case of unclosed environments). environment_name is currently used after the loop to consume the matching \end{name}, but it's reserved for future strict matching (verify the \end's argument matches the expected name).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_content_until_end" that takes parser_ptr as Integer, environment_name as String returns Integer:
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_END:

                Note: Check if this is our end
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_content_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Consume \end{environment_name}
    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_END:
        proc advance from parser_ptr
        proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    Return content_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
The content-item dispatcher branches on token type into specialized parsers (sectioning, environments, formatting, math, citations, references, labels, list items, commands, text, groups). Order doesn't affect correctness because the types are mutually exclusive, but we keep semantically-related items grouped (math forms together, citation forms together) for readability. Unknown tokens advance silently to keep recovery bounded.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_content_item" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

    Note: Sectioning commands
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_PART or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_CHAPTER or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_SECTION or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_SUBSECTION or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_SUBSUBSECTION:
        Return proc parse_section from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Environments
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_BEGIN:
        Return proc parse_environment from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Text formatting commands
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_TEXTBF or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_TEXTIT or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_TEXTTT or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EMPH or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_UNDERLINE:
        Return proc parse_text_formatting from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Math mode
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_INLINE_START:
        Return proc parse_inline_math from parser_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_DISPLAY_START or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_BRACKET_START:
        Return proc parse_display_math from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Citations and references
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_CITE:
        Return proc parse_citation from parser_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_REF or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_PAGEREF:
        Return proc parse_reference from parser_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LABEL:
        Return proc parse_label from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: List item
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_ITEM:
        Return proc parse_list_item from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Generic command
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_COMMAND:
        Return proc parse_command from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Text
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_TEXT:
        Return proc parse_text from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Group
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Return proc parse_group from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Unknown token, skip it
    proc advance from parser_ptr
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Sectioning
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sectioning commands (\part, \chapter, \section, \subsection, \subsubsection) share the same syntax: optional short title in [...] followed by required title in {...}. We capture the specific section-type token (stored at offset 8) so the AST distinguishes levels without scanning the lexeme. Short title is recorded as a separate child so TOC generation can use it without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_section" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let section_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 40

    proc write_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 0, NODE_SECTION

    Note: Get section type
    Let section_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let section_type be proc read_integer from Memory with section_token, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 8, section_type

    Note: Parse optional short title
    Let short_title_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set short_title_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 16, short_title_ptr

    Note: Parse required title
    Let title_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 24, title_ptr

    Return section_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Environment Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
A LaTeX environment is "\begin{name}[params]content\end{name}"; we capture name, optional params, and the content list. Name extraction (via extract_text_from_arg) is needed because the matching \end must reference the same name — that name string also drives the content-loop termination check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_environment" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let env_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 40

    proc write_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 0, NODE_ENVIRONMENT

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_BEGIN

    Note: Get environment name
    Let name_arg be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 8, name_arg

    Note: Parse optional parameters (for some environments)
    Let params_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set params_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 16, params_ptr

    Note: Parse environment content
    Note: Extract environment name from argument for matching
    Let env_name_str be proc extract_text_from_arg from name_arg

    Let content_ptr be proc parse_content_until_end with parser_ptr, env_name_str

    proc write_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 24, content_ptr

    Return env_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Math Mode Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inline math is delimited by $ on both ends; content is parsed via parse_math_item (which handles superscripts, subscripts, and math-specific commands). EOF inside math is recorded as "Unclosed inline math" so users get a precise diagnostic rather than a cascading error in the surrounding text.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_inline_math" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let math_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 0, NODE_MATH_INLINE

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_INLINE_START

    Note: Parse math content until closing $
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_INLINE_END:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unclosed inline math"
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_math_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_INLINE_END

    proc write_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8, content_list

    Return math_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Display math has two delimiter conventions ($$...$$ and \[...\]); we look at the opening delimiter to pick the matching close. The two forms are semantically equivalent so they produce the same NODE_MATH_DISPLAY tag; only the delimiter pair differs. Mismatched openers/closers cause a parse error rather than silent misparse.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_display_math" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let math_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 0, NODE_MATH_DISPLAY

    Let start_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

    proc advance from parser_ptr  Note: Consume opening delimiter

    Note: Determine closing delimiter type
    Let end_type be LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_DISPLAY_END

    If start_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_BRACKET_START:
        Set end_type to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_MATH_BRACKET_END
    End If

    Note: Parse math content
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to end_type:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unclosed display math"
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_math_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser_ptr, end_type

    proc write_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8, content_list

    Return math_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Math-mode items differ from text-mode items because superscript (^) and subscript (_) are operators only in math context. Falls through to parse_script for scripts, parse_group for {...}, parse_command for math commands; everything else advances as a single math token. Returning 0 on unknowns lets the math loop continue without polluting the AST with stray items.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_math_item" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a single math mode item (command, text, subscript, superscript, etc.).
    @End Reasoning

    Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

    Note: Math commands
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_FRAC or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_SQRT or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_SUM or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_INT or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_PROD or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LIM:
        Return proc parse_command from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Subscript and superscript
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_UNDERSCORE or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_CARET:
        Return proc parse_script from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Groups in math mode
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Return proc parse_group from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Generic command
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_COMMAND:
        Return proc parse_command from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Text in math mode
    If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_TEXT:
        Return proc parse_text from parser_ptr
    End If

    Note: Unknown, skip
    proc advance from parser_ptr
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scripts (^ for superscript, _ for subscript) take EITHER a single math item OR a braced group, by TeX convention: "x^2" applies to just the 2 but "x^{ab}" applies to ab. We check for an opening brace to choose between parse_group and parse_math_item. The script_type at offset 8 distinguishes super- from subscript.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_script" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let script_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with script_ptr, 0, NODE_COMMAND

    Let script_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let script_type be proc read_integer from Memory with script_token, 0

    proc write_integer from Memory with script_ptr, 8, script_type

    Note: Parse the script content (either a single token or a group)
    Let content_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Set content_ptr to proc parse_group from parser_ptr
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single character/command
        Set content_ptr to proc parse_math_item from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with script_ptr, 16, content_ptr

    Return script_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Text Formatting
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Formatting commands (\textbf, \textit, \texttt, \emph, \underline) share the same signature: command followed by exactly one required argument. We capture the specific format type at offset 8 so backends can map each to the right output (bold/italic/monospace/emphasis/underline in HTML, *bold* in Markdown, etc.).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_text_formatting" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let format_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with format_ptr, 0, NODE_TEXT_FORMATTING

    Let format_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let format_type be proc read_integer from Memory with format_token, 0

    proc write_integer from Memory with format_ptr, 8, format_type

    Note: Parse the text argument
    Let text_arg be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with format_ptr, 16, text_arg

    Return format_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Citations and References
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
\cite supports optional inline note (\cite[p.~42]{key}) plus the required citation key list. Both are stored separately so a backend can emit "Smith 2020, p. 42" or just "Smith 2020" depending on output style. Multiple keys (comma-separated) inside the {} are parsed by the required-argument scanner.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_citation" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cite_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with cite_ptr, 0, NODE_CITATION

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_CITE

    Note: Optional note
    Let note_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set note_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with cite_ptr, 8, note_ptr

    Note: Citation key
    Let key_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with cite_ptr, 16, key_ptr

    Return cite_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
\ref and \pageref produce different output (section number vs page number) but share the same syntax; we capture the specific ref_type at offset 8 so backends can render them distinctly while sharing the parser path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_reference" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ref_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with ref_ptr, 0, NODE_REFERENCE

    Let ref_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let ref_type be proc read_integer from Memory with ref_token, 0

    proc write_integer from Memory with ref_ptr, 8, ref_type

    Note: Label key
    Let label_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with ref_ptr, 16, label_ptr

    Return ref_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
\label has a single required key argument; the key becomes the target of subsequent \ref/\pageref lookups. We use a smaller (24-byte) record since there are no options to record.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_label" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let label_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with label_ptr, 0, NODE_LABEL

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LABEL

    Note: Label key
    Let key_ptr be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr

    proc write_integer from Memory with label_ptr, 8, key_ptr

    Return label_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: List Items
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
\item content runs until the next \item or \end (no explicit terminator); this is a TeX-specific quirk we honor by terminating the content loop on either token. Optional label in [] captures custom bullet markers in itemize/description environments. content_list is built incrementally as we recurse into parse_content_item for each sub-element.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_list_item" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let item_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32

    proc write_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0, NODE_LIST_ITEM

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_ITEM

    Note: Optional label
    Let label_ptr be 0

    If proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set label_ptr to proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
    End If

    proc write_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 8, label_ptr

    Note: Parse item content until next \item or \end
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_ITEM or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_END or token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let item be proc parse_content_item from parser_ptr

            If item is not equal to 0:
                proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc write_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 16, content_list

    Return item_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Generic Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
The generic command parser handles any \name[opts][opts]...{args}{args}... shape. We accept arbitrarily many optional and required arguments in their natural order so user-defined commands like \mycmd[a][b]{c}{d} round-trip correctly. The two lists (optional_args, required_args) at offsets 16/24 keep the distinction without baking arity assumptions into the AST.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_command" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cmd_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 40

    proc write_integer from Memory with cmd_ptr, 0, NODE_COMMAND

    Let cmd_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let cmd_name be proc read_string from Memory with cmd_token, 8

    proc write_string from Memory with cmd_ptr, 8, cmd_name

    Note: Parse optional arguments
    Let optional_args be proc create_list from ListCore

    While proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Let opt_arg be proc parse_optional_argument from parser_ptr
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with optional_args, opt_arg
    End While

    proc write_integer from Memory with cmd_ptr, 16, optional_args

    Note: Parse required arguments
    Let required_args be proc create_list from ListCore

    While proc peek_type with parser_ptr is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Let req_arg be proc parse_required_argument from parser_ptr
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with required_args, req_arg
    End While

    proc write_integer from Memory with cmd_ptr, 24, required_args

    Return cmd_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Plain text tokens are wrapped in NODE_TEXT_BLOCK records carrying the raw text string; this thin wrapping is uniform with all other content nodes so consumers iterate without polymorphism. The 16-byte record is just type + text pointer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_text" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let text_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 16

    proc write_integer from Memory with text_ptr, 0, NODE_TEXT_BLOCK

    Let text_token be proc advance from parser_ptr
    Let text_content be proc read_string from Memory with text_token, 8

    proc write_string from Memory with text_ptr, 8, text_content

    Return text_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
A group {...} is a scope-defining construct in TeX (e.g., {\bfseries text} bolds only inside the braces). Parsing as a NODE_GROUP preserves the scoping for backends that respect it. Unclosed groups at EOF emit a recoverable error and exit cleanly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_group" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let group_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 16

    proc write_integer from Memory with group_ptr, 0, NODE_GROUP

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE

    Note: Parse content until closing brace
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unclosed group"
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_content_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACE

    proc write_integer from Memory with group_ptr, 8, content_list

    Return group_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Argument Parsing
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Optional arguments are delimited by [...] and may contain arbitrary content (other commands, text, math). The is_optional=0 flag at offset 8 distinguishes optional from required at consumption time. Content recursion uses parse_content_item so nested commands inside [] work uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_optional_argument" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let arg_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 0, NODE_ARGUMENT

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 8, 0  Note: is_optional = true

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET

    Note: Parse content until closing bracket
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unclosed optional argument"
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_content_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 16, content_list

    Return arg_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Required arguments use {...} and share the same record shape with optional arguments, distinguished only by the is_optional=1 (here "is_required") flag. Same content recursion as optional args ensures nested structure works correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_required_argument" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let arg_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 0, NODE_ARGUMENT

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 8, 1  Note: is_required = true

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_LBRACE

    Note: Parse content until closing brace
    Let content_list be proc create_list from ListCore

    Let continue be 1

    While continue is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_type from parser_ptr

        If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_EOF:

                proc add_parse_error with parser_ptr, "Unclosed required argument"
                Set continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let item be proc parse_content_item from parser_ptr

                If item is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_to_list from ListCore with content_list, item
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser_ptr, LaTeXLexer.TOKEN_RBRACE

    proc write_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 16, content_list

    Return arg_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Environment-name matching requires the plain text from the {name} argument; we walk into the content list, fetch the first item, and return its text if it's a NODE_TEXT_BLOCK. This is intentionally lenient — empty argument, null content, non-text first item, all degrade gracefully to "" so the caller can decide whether to error or fall back.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_text_from_arg" that takes arg_ptr as Integer returns String:
    If arg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let content_list be proc read_integer from Memory with arg_ptr, 16

    If content_list is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let list_size be proc get_list_size from ListCore with content_list

    If list_size is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Note: Get first item
    Let first_item be proc get_from_list from ListCore with content_list, 0

    If first_item is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let node_type be proc read_integer from Memory with first_item, 0

    If node_type is equal to NODE_TEXT_BLOCK:
        Return proc read_string from Memory with first_item, 8
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each error records its position by snapshotting the current token's line/column at offset 24/32; if there's no current token (past EOF) we use 0/0 so the diagnostic still has a well-defined value. The 24-byte error record (message + line + column) matches the lexer's error shape for unified consumption.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_parse_error" that takes parser_ptr as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Let token_ptr be proc peek from parser_ptr
    Let line be 0
    Let column be 0

    If token_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Set line to proc read_integer from Memory with token_ptr, 24
        Set column to proc read_integer from Memory with token_ptr, 32
    End If

    Let error_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 24
    proc write_string from Memory with error_ptr, 0, message
    proc write_integer from Memory with error_ptr, 8, line
    proc write_integer from Memory with error_ptr, 16, column

    Let errors_list be proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 16
    proc add_to_list from ListCore with errors_list, error_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor returns the raw error list pointer (no copy); the orchestrator iterates it for diagnostic display. The list is owned by the parser for its lifetime so callers must consume errors before freeing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_errors" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 16
End Process
